    "source_sections": {
      "references": "",
      "remarks": "Erd\\H{o}s suggests that if the answer is no one could consider the variant where we assume that $S$ is Sidon (i.e. all $a+b$ with $a,b\\in S$ are distinct, aside from the trivial coincidences).\n\nIn the comments Dillies gives a positive proof of this, found by AlphaProof: in other words, if $S\\subset \\mathbb{R}$ is a Sidon set then there exists $A\\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\\backslash S$ of cardinality continuum such that $A+A\\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\\backslash S$."
    },
